 201	## Implementation Standards
 202	
 203	### Code Organization
 204	```
 205	src/
 206	├── modules/ # Core modules (session, memory, execution)
 207	│ ├── [module]/
 208	│ │ ├── index.ts # Public API
 209	│ │ ├── types.ts # Type definitions
 210	│ │ ├── implementation.ts # Core logic
 211	│ │ ├── errors.ts # Module-specific errors
 212	│ │ └── __tests__/ # Comprehensive tests
 213	├── agents/ # Agent implementations
 214	│ ├── base/ # Foundation for all agents
 215	│ ├── llm/ # LLM-specific agent
 216	│ └── graph/ # Workflow orchestration
 217	├── shared/ # Shared utilities
 218	└── examples/ # Usage examples
 219	```
 220	
 221	### Naming Conventions
 222	```typescript
 223	// Interfaces: I prefix for injected dependencies
 224	interface IStorage { }
 225	interface ILogger { }
 226	
 227	// Types: Descriptive names, no prefix
 228	type AgentConfig = { };
 229	type ExecutionState = { };
 230	
 231	// Classes: Noun phrases
 232	class ConversationMemory { }
 233	class GraphExecutionEngine { }
 234	
 235	// Methods: Verb phrases that describe action
 236	async executeWorkflow(): Promise<Result> { }
 237	validateConfiguration(config: Config): void { }
 238	
 239	// Events: Past tense for completed, present for ongoing
 240	emit('workflowCompleted', result);
 241	emit('nodeExecuting', nodeId);
 242	
 243	// Constants: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE
 244	const MAX_RETRY_ATTEMPTS = 3;
 245	const DEFAULT_TIMEOUT_MS = 30000;
 246	```
 247	
 248	### Error Handling Philosophy
 249	1. **Fail Fast**: Detect problems early
 250	2. **Fail Clearly**: Explain what went wrong
 251	3. **Fail Helpfully**: Suggest how to fix it
 252	4. **Fail Safely**: Don't corrupt state
 253	
 254	### Testing Philosophy
 255	1. **Test Behavior, Not Implementation**
 256	2. **Test Edge Cases Explicitly**
 257	3. **Test Error Conditions**
 258	4. **Test Performance Critical Paths**
 259	5. **Test Integration Points**
 260	
 261	### Documentation Philosophy
 262	1. **Document Why, Not What**
 263	2. **Examples Are Worth 1000 Words**
 264	3. **Keep Docs Next to Code**
 265	4. **Update Docs With Code**
 266	
 267	## Decision Making Framework
 268	
 269	When facing architectural decisions, ask:
 270	
 271	1. **Does it make the API simpler?**
 272	 - If no, reconsider the approach
 273	
 274	2. **Does it hide complexity from users?**
 275	 - If no, find a better abstraction
 276	
 277	3. **Is it testable in isolation?**
 278	 - If no, refactor for testability
 279	
 280	4. **Will it scale to 1000x current load?**
 281	 - If no, document the limitations
 282	
 283	5. **Can it recover from failures?**
 284	 - If no, add resilience
 285	
 286	6. **Is it secure by default?**
 287	 - If no, it's not ready
 288	
 289	7. **Will developers understand it in 6 months?**
 290	 - If no, improve documentation
 291	
 292	## Remember
 293	
 294	> "Any fool can write code that a computer can understand. Good programmers write code that humans can understand." - Martin Fowler
 295	
 296	We're not just writing code. We're crafting a system that other developers will build their dreams upon. Every line matters. Every comment teaches. Every test protects.
 297	
 298	**Do the hard work. Be diligent. Build something extraordinary.**
